04245nam a22004935i 9780226283883DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262838837 a10.7208/97802262838832doi  a(DE-B1597)524046  a(OCoLC)496099313  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLB2342b.G37 2009eb 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a378.1/0609732221 aGarland, James C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSaving Alma Mater :bA Rescue Plan for America's Public Universities /cJames C. Garland. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b7 line drawings, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. A Primer on Public Higher Education Economics -- tPart II. The Academic Culture of Freedom and Waste -- tPart III. Renegotiating the Public Compact -- tPostscript -- tAppendix A: The Miami University Tuition Plan -- tAppendix B: The Impact of Competition on Public University Tuition, Costs, and Revenue -- tAppendix C: Suggested Readings -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica’s public universities educate 80% of our nation’s college students. But in the wake of rising demands on state treasuries, changing demographics, growing income inequality, and legislative indifference, many of these institutions have fallen into decline. Tuition costs have skyrocketed, class sizes have gone up, the number of courses offered has gone down, and the overall quality of education has decreased significantly. Here James C. Garland draws on more than thirty years of experience as a professor, administrator, and university president to argue that a new compact between state government and public universities is needed to make these schools more affordable and financially secure. Saving Alma Mater challenges a change-resistant culture in academia that places too low a premium on efficiency and productivity. Seeing a crisis of campus leadership, Garland takes state legislators to task for perpetuating the decay of their public university systems and calls for reforms in the way university presidents and governing boards are selected. He concludes that the era is long past when state appropriations can enable public universities to keep their fees low and affordable. Saving Alma Mater thus calls for the partial deregulation of public universities and a phase-out of their state appropriations. Garland’s plan would tie university revenues to their performance and exploit the competitive pressures of the academic marketplace to control costs, rein in tuition, and make schools more responsive to student needs. A much-needed blueprint for reform based on Garland’s real-life successes as the head of Miami University of Ohio, Saving Alma Mater will be essential for anyone concerned with the costs and quality of higher education in America today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPublic universities and collegeszUnited StatesxFinance. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226283883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226283883.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles